      "text": "UNITED STATES OF AMERICA\nBEFORE THE\nFEDERAL ENERGY REGULATORY COMMISSION\nImprovements to Generator )\nInterconnection Procedures and ) Docket No. RM22-14-000\nAgreements )\nINITIAL COMMENTS OF ISO NEW ENGLAND INC.\nISO New England Inc. (“ISO-NE” or “ISO”) respectfully submits these comments in \nresponse to the Notice of Proposed Rulemaking on Improvements to Generator Interconnection \nProcedures and Agreements that the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission’s (“Commission”) \nissued on June 16, 2022, in the above-captioned proceeding.1 \nI. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY\nThe Commission’s proposed rule is the second effort stemming from its July 15, 2021 \nAdvanced Notice of Proposed Rulemaking,2 which sought to examine the need for reforms in \nregional transmission planning and generator interconnection processes established in Order Nos. \n \n1\nSee Improvements to Generator Interconnection Procedures and Agreements, 179 FERC ¶ 61,194 (2022) \n(“NOPR”). New England’s Interconnection Procedures are contained in Schedules 22, 23 and 25 of Section \nII of the ISO New England Transmission, Markets and Services Tariff (“Tariff”), which contains the Open \nAccess Transmission Tariff (“OATT”). Schedule 22 contains the Large Generator Interconnection \nProcedures and Interconnection Agreement (“Schedule 22” or “LGIP”); Schedule 23 contains the Small \nGenerator Interconnection Procedures and Interconnection Agreement (“Schedule 23” or “SGIP”), and \nSchedule 25 contains the Elective Transmission Upgrade Interconnection Procedures and Interconnection \nAgreement (“Schedule 25” or “ETU IP”).\n2 Building for the Future Through Electric Regional Transmission Planning and Cost Allocation and \nGenerator Interconnection, Advance Notice of Proposed Rulemaking, 176 FERC ¶ 61,024 (July 15, 2021) \n(“ANOPR”); Initial Comments of ISO New Inc., Docket No. RM21-17-000 (Oct. 12, 2021) (“ANOPR\nComments”).\n2\n2003, 890, and 1000.3 In the NOPR, the Commission proposes to: “(1) implement a first-ready, \nfirst-served cluster study process, (2) increase the speed of interconnection queue processing, and \n(3) incorporate technological advancements into the interconnection process,” for the Large \nGenerating Facilities.\n4\n The Commission further proposes to “incorporate alternative transmission \ntechnologies into the interconnection process and to provide modeling and performance \nrequirements for non-synchronous generators” for Small Generating Facilities.\n5\n \nIn New England, the states have set aggressive decarbonization goals, which are expected \nto drive the dramatic transformation of the resource mix in the region from conventional generators \nto renewable resources, and increase demand through the electrification of the economy.\n6\n \nAchieving this clean energy transition safely and reliably depends, in part, on an efficient \ninterconnection process. Based on the ISO’s interconnection queue as of March 2022, the future \nresource mix proposed to meet the increasing demand comprises 96% renewable resources, \ntotaling approximately 30,000 MW, including approximately 20,000 MW of wind facilities. 7 \nThanks to significant Tariff improvements proposed jointly with the New England Participant \nTransmission Owners (“PTOs”) and the New England Power Pool (“NEPOOL”), and supported \nby the New England states, the region’s existing Interconnection Procedures are facilitating \n \n3\nStandardization of Generator Interconnection Agreements and Procedures, 104 FERC ¶ 61,103 (2003) \n(“Order No. 2003”); Preventing Undue Discrimination and Preference in Transmission Service, 118 FERC \n¶ 61,119 (2007) (“Order No. 890”); Transmission Planning and Cost Allocation by Transmission Owning \nand Operating Public Utilities, 136 FERC ¶ 61,051 (2011) (“Order No. 1000”).\n4 NOPR at P 4.\n5\nId. at P 5. \n6\nFor additional details, see ISO New England Inc.’s 2022 Regional Electric Outlook, available on the ISO\u0002NE website at https://www.iso-ne.com/static-assets/documents/2022/06/2022_reo.pdf (“2022 REO”).\n7\nSee 2022 REO at 11, 15.\n3\ndevelopment of significant amounts of renewable generation. The ISO, however, agrees with the \nCommission’s statements in the NOPR that the process can be more efficient.\n8\nAs discussed in Sections III and IV below, many of the interconnection reforms that ISO\u0002NE has implemented since Order Nos. 2003 and 2006 are consistent with the spirit of the \nCommission’s proposed interconnection reforms in the NOPR. These include improvements to \nintegrate the interconnection queue with the Forward Capacity Market (“FCM”), incorporate\nElective Transmission Upgrades (“ETU”) into the interconnection process, and establish a limited \ncluster study process.\nAccordingly, ISO-NE respectfully requests that the Commission not adopt uniform or \nprescriptive compliance requirements that fail to account for these regional variations in any final \nrule issued in this proceeding. Instead, the ISO requests that the Commission recognize existing\nregional differences and allow the necessary flexibility for the ISO to develop a compliance \napproach that builds on the region’s accomplishments, consistent with the Commission’s long\u0002standing principles. This will allow for incorporation of the elements proposed by the Commission \ninto existing processes and procedures in a way that best meets the needs of the region.\nWith respect to the specific reforms proposed in the NOPR, ISO-NE offers the following \ncomments, discussed in further detail below: \n The NOPR appropriately recognizes that significant trade-offs are involved when \npursuing a change as expansive as the first-ready, first-served construct proposed. \nUnder the proposal, ISO-NE’s study efforts would be focused on fewer projects \nthat are more likely to be constructed. However, this trade-off must be realistic. \n Higher study completion expectations and the elimination of the reasonable efforts \nstandard would require that study effort be focused on projects that are sufficiently \nviable, necessitate less flexibility for midstream project changes/ability to consider \nalternatives, and require stricter expectations for the completion of all aspects of \nthe process, such as the preparation of transmission upgrade cost-estimates. \n \n8\nSee e.g. NOPR at PP 3, 22.\n4\n New England has made several enhancements to the Interconnection Procedures in \nrecent years including the integration of the interconnection process with the FCM, \nthe inclusion of a process for ETUs, and targeted clustering. The Commission \nshould respect these enhancements in any final rule and allow the ISO to build upon \nthem for compliance purposes. \n The first-ready, first-served construct should apply to all interconnection \nprocedures, not just to large generators, to avoid the operation of multiple, separate \nqueues with fundamentally different expectations in terms of studies and \ntimeframes. \nII. COMMUNICATIONS\nISO-NE is the independent, private, nonprofit entity that serves as the Regional \nTransmission Organization (“RTO”) for New England. The ISO operates the New England bulk \npower system and administers New England’s organized wholesale electricity market pursuant to \nthe Tariff and the Transmission Operating Agreement (“TOA”) with the New England \nParticipating Transmission Owners (“PTO”). As the RTO, the ISO has the responsibility to protect \nthe short-term reliability of the New England Control Area and to plan and operate the system \naccording to reliability standards established by the ISO, the Northeast Power Coordinating \nCouncil, Inc. (“NPCC”) and the North American Electric Reliability Corporation (“NERC”).\nCorrespondence and communications in this proceeding should be addressed to:\nGraham Jesmer\nISO New England Inc.\nOne Sullivan Road\nHolyoke, MA 01040-2841\nTel: (413) 540-4557\nFax: (413) 535-4379\nE-mail: gjesmer@iso-ne.com \n5\nIII. BACKGROUND \nA. Basis for the NOPR\nThe NOPR seeks to advance the efforts the Commission initiated through the ANOPR to \nupdate its existing interconnection policies to bring r",
